[6] Indonesia - animal health and food safety
Date: 2 Nov 2010
Source: Beritajakarta.com [edited]
<http://www.beritajakarta.com/2008/en/newsview.aspx?idwil=0&id=17192>


To ensure the health conditions of sacrificial animals ahead of Eid al-Adha
holiday, which is expected to fall on 17 Nov 2010, Jakarta capital city
government plans to conduct health checks on the sacrificial animals from
Dd-7 to Dd+3. A total of 750 officers will be deployed to carry out the
checks at 1577 animal shelters and 1795 slaughterhouses in Jakarta area.

Head of Jakarta Maritime and Fishery Agency, Ipih Royani, said the officers
would not only carry out health examinations on sacrificial animals but
also supervise the slaughtering process in order to ensure it runs in
accordance with the provisions of Islamic law.

Ipih disclosed that the 750 technical officers consisted of 300 people from
Bogor Agricultural University (IPB), 25 people from the Indonesian
Veterinary Association (PDHI) of Jakarta chapter, and 425 from Jakarta
Marine and Fishery Agency itself.

"We must ensure the health of all sacrificial animals. The animals must be
free from animal diseases like anthrax and PMK [Penyakit Mulu dan Kuku,
Indonesian for FMD]. In addition, the slaughtering process must also be in
accordance with the provisions of Islamic law," said Ipih Royani on Tuesday
[2 Nov 2010].

Ipih further said Jakarta Maritime and Fishery Agency had also conducted
preventive measures to guarantee all sacrificial animals distributed to
Jakarta are healthy. One of them is by stressing that each animal entering
the capital area must be provided a with written medical license from a
veterinarian in the area of origin. "As of now, we have yet identified
animals contracting both diseases. We continue to conduct monitoring," said
Ipih. "The main characteristic of a sick animal is a high body temperature
(above 40 C). We'll take the blood samples of suspected animals to be
tested in our laboratory. If tested positive of the 2 diseases, the animals
will be immediately destroyed. They should not be consumed by humans," Ipih
concluded.

