[7] Jordan - imports from Ethiopia, Sudan, Romania
Date: 27 Oct 2010
Source: Jordan Times [summarised, edited]
<http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=31317>


Thousands of sheep will arrive from Sudan on Friday [29 Oct 2010] as part
of the National Company for Food Security's (NCFS) preparations for Eid Al
Adha sacrifices, according to the company's director.

"A total of 12 000 sheep will arrive in the Kingdom from Sudan," NCFS
Director General Wael Shqeirat told The Jordan Times over the phone on
Tuesday [26 Oct 2010], adding that 10 000 Romanian sheep have already been
imported, while 14 000 will soon be imported from Ethiopia.

President of the Consumer Protection Society (CPS) Mohammad Obeidat said
there is "ambiguity" surrounding the number of livestock to be imported,
expected around 16 Nov 2010. "Importers should provide precise figures on
the numbers of sheep they will import to ensure that the available
livestock cover the Kingdom's needs for Eid sacrifices," Obeidat told The
Jordan Times. He added that even the NCFS has not provided exact numbers of
sheep it will import ahead of Eid, and thus, the society cannot predict the
prices of sheep to be sold during the Muslim holiday.

Butchers and importers, however, denied that meat prices had risen at all,
saying that sales of red meat have been "surprisingly poor." Butchers in
Amman, Irbid and Zarqa also complained of "very low" demand for meat.

[byline: Laila Azzeh]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The annual Hajj pilgrimage to Mecca, the world's largest annual gathering,
will begin this year on 14 Nov 2010. The pilgrimage's end is marked by Eid
al-Adha (Feast of Sacrifice, also Id ul-Adha, Eidul Azha). This Muslim
3-day festival commemorates the biblical patriarch Ibrahim's (or Abraham's)
willingness to sacrifice his son Ismail (or Ishmael) in obedience to a
command from Allah. It always falls on the 10th of Dhul al-Hijja, the 12th
and final month in the Islamic calendar, and terminates on the 13th. This
year [2010], the Eid has been set to start on 16 Nov 2010.

A considerable proportion of the meat from animals slaughtered during Eid
al-Adha, which is the most important feast of the Muslim calendar, is
distributed to the needy and the poor.

The feast, celebrated throughout the world, incorporates the slaughter of
sheep, goats, cattle and camels. Their number -- in Saudi Arabia alone --
is a 7-digit figure. Obviously, the transportation and slaughtering
procedures of such numbers, within a few days, is a huge animal-health and
food-safety control undertaking everywhere. It is, though, of particular
weight in Saudi Arabia, where it is combined with the gathering of more
than 2 million pilgrims from all parts of the globe.

The biohazard, as related to animal and zoonotic diseases, is proportional
to the animal disease situation in the countries of origin. Among the
countries mentioned as exporters to Saudi Arabia and to other Middle
Eastern trade partners, subscribers would have noticed Sudan, Somali and
Ethiopia, countries which may be regarded as requiring special attention
concerning their animal disease situation.

In 2007, Rift Valley fever was one of the main concerns; fortunately, this
does not seem to be the case this year [2010], although precaution is
always in place. Among the epizootic ruminant diseases which are reportedly
endemic in the said 3 exporting countries, one will find contagious bovine
pleuropneumonia, contagious caprine pleuropneumonia, FMD, haemorrhagic
septicaemia, heartwater, lumpy skin disease, PPR, sheep pox/goat pox.

Steps to safeguard the health of slaughter-animals from these countries
should include prescribed veterinary control and surveillance activities
prior to and during their transportation, official state-controlled
quarantine facilities and -- following their importation -- full separation
from local livestock and meticulous ante- and postmortem veterinary
inspections. - Mod.AS]
